{"altmetric_id":15416992,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":44,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":23},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":21,"unique_users":["Brianxbio","HBCUSTEM","JeanYvesMasson","HoatlinLab","ismailelghitani","MeoYo","GelotCam","DrBillonPierre","ZaminIqbal","josefra1975","EpigeneticsGuy","reny_67","Jones_MJK","MolecularCell","jlwalker97","cdc2kinase","HeartNati0n","srigsri23","DocDellaire","BHCRI","Tony7doc"],"posts_count":23}},"selected_quotes":["ATR acts after DNA end resection to promote HR. Great article","ATR regulation of HR (Buisson 2017 Mol. Cell) - great to collaborate with the Masson and Zou Group\u2026","ATR regulation of HR (Buisson 2017 Mol. Cell) - great to collaborate with the Masson and Zou Groups @JeanYvesMasson","@BHCRI Our recent paper, collab with"],"citation":{"abstract":"ATR is a key regulator of cell-cycle checkpoints and homologous recombination (HR). Paradoxically, ATR inhibits CDKs during checkpoint responses, but CDK activity is required for efficient HR. Here, we show that ATR promotes HR after CDK-driven DNA end resection. ATR stimulates the BRCA1-PALB2 interaction after DNA damage and promotes PALB2 localization to DNA damage sites. ATR enhances BRCA1-PALB2 binding at least in part by inhibiting\u00a0CDKs. The optimal interaction of BRCA1 and PALB2 requires phosphorylation of PALB2 at S59, an ATR site, and hypo-phosphorylation of S64, a CDK site. The PALB2-S59A\/S64E mutant is defective for localization to DNA damage sites and HR, whereas the PALB2-S59E\/S64A mutant partially bypasses ATR for its localization. Thus, HR is a biphasic process requiring both high-CDK and low-CDK periods. As exemplified by the regulation of PALB2 by ATR, ATR promotes HR by orchestrating a \"CDK-to-ATR switch\" post-resection, directly coupling the checkpoint to HR.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa5163cf058f6100037ba","authors":["R\u00e9mi Buisson","Joshi Niraj","Am\u00e9lie Rodrigue","Chu Kwen Ho","Johannes Kreuzer","Tzeh Keong Foo","Emil